These fourteen (14) individual elements of this prevention program work together to prevent accidental chemical releases. MPLX and its employees are committed to the standards required by these management programs. In addition to the above elements, MPLX also has specific prevention measures that are employed as part of the Terminal's operating procedures and engineering/administrative controls to help identify/contain/control a release and reduce the resulting potential impacts. These are briefly summarized as follows:

General Risk Reduction and Safety Measures

-Engineering and construction in accordance with recognized industry and corporate standards;
-Equipment properly designed with protection from overpressure (hydrostatic/thermal pressure relief valves, etc.);
-Updated technical drawings, Piping & Instrument Diagrams and Process/Block Flow Diagrams;
-Operating systems monitored and controlled by trained Operators;
-Redundant control systems;
-Manual shutdown devices for critical systems;
-Scheduled inspection and testing of safety devices;
-Limited/secured facility access;
-Regular safety meetings and safety awareness programs;
-Routinely scheduled safety inspections and audits; and
-Frequent unit surveillance by operators.

General Release Mitigation:

The worst-case release quantity is based on the total volume of the process conservatively assuming all lines are filled.  The alternate-case release quantity is based on a reported per minute rate for 10 minutes assuming connection to a transport.

-Process and remotely operated shut-offs to limit release quantity (also actuated via a fusible element);
-Strategically located valves to isolate leaks; and
-Low-emission transport coupler, "Smart-Hose" with design break-away and self-closing valves on each end.

